Weak Stationary Process

In a weak stationary time series, there is

  1. No systematic change in mean (no trend)
  2. No systematic change in variance
  3. No periodic variations

The properties of one section of a data are much like the properties of the other sections of the data
For an non-stationary time series, we will do some transformations to get stationary time series

Random Process (or Stochastic Process)

A discrete stochastic process is a family of random variables structured as a sequence (finite or infinite) and has a discrete time index, denoted $X_t$
So, $X_1,X_2,X_3,.........X_N$ is a random process where each of $X_t$ is a random variable
We can obtain properties of each $X_t$ if have the luxury of observing multiple trajectories of a random process
For example the below table shows multiple trajectories of a single random process $X_1,X_2,X_3,.........X_7$
For each random variable of the sequence we can find distribution if we have large number of trajectories

Auto-covariance

Given a stochastic process, the autocovariance is a function that gives the covariance of the process with itself at pairs of time points.
where $t_1$ and $t_2$ are two moments in time
Here, $t_2-t_1=\tau$ is termed as 'lag'
In the above example we can find $covar(X_2,X_5)$ which is actually 'auto-covariance' between $2^{nd}$ and $5^{th}$ time step of the random process.

Auto-correlation

Similar to auto-covariance function we can define auto-correlation function as correlation of the process with itself at pairs of time points.
Autocorrelation Function, $ \rho(t_1,t_2) = \frac{E[(X(t_1)-\mu(t_1))(X(t_2)-\mu(t_2))]}{\sigma_{t_1} \sigma_{t_2}} = \frac{\gamma(t_1,t_2)}{\sigma_{t_1} \sigma_{t_2}}$


A stochastic process is a rather complicated thing. To fully specify its structure we would need to know the joint distribution of the full set of random variables. So, we must know all possible trajectories.

But we generally have one sequence !!!!

We usually just have one sequentially observed data set and must infer the properties of the generating process from this single trajectory.

Stationarity (strictly stationary)

We can work using a single trajectory if process is stationary (strictly stationary)
$\implies$ In this setting, if we shift our attention by a distance we will still have the same joint distribution. In particular, the joint distribution only depends upon our lag spacings. This is actually quite profound and yields beautifully simplifying results.

Weak Stationarity

With these, putting =0

If weak stationarity is assumed we get enough values (or pairs) from a single a trajectory to estimate variance, auto-covariance and auto-correlation

Plot of autocorrelation for a time series for different lags is called correlogram

Purely Random Process (is a weakly stationary process)

$X_t = Z_t$
$X_t$ = Value at time t
$Z_t$ = White noise $(Normal(\mu,\sigma^2)).$At each time the $Z_t$ is a random variable from a normal distribution. So, there will be no correlation between $Z_t$'s (or $X_t$'s) at different t's

In[5]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import statsmodels.tsa.stattools as ts
import Toggle
np.random.seed(5)
x = np.random.normal(loc=0.0,scale=1.0,size=100)
plt.figure(figsize=(24,6))
plt.subplot(1,3,1)
plt.title("Purely Random Process")
plt.plot(x)

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
acovf_x = ts.acovf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlag=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acovf_x)),height=acovf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.title("Auto Covariance-Purely Random Process")

plt.subplot(1,3,3)
acorf_x = ts.acf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlags=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acorf_x)),height=acorf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Auto Correlation-Purely Random Process")
#plt.plot(x)
plt.show()
Toggle.hide_toggle()

Random Walk (is not a weakly stationary process)

$X_t = X_{t-1} + Z_t$
We can prove by expanding $X_t$ into sum of consecutive $Z_t$'s that $E[X_t]$ and $var(X_t)$ is dependent on $t$.

In[6]:
x = []
x.append(0)
np.random.seed(5)
for i in range(1,100):
    z = np.random.normal(size=1)[0]
    x.append(x[i-1] + z)
    
plt.figure(figsize=(24,12))
plt.subplot(2,3,1)
plt.title("Random Walk")
plt.plot(x)

plt.subplot(2,3,2)
acovf_x = ts.acovf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlag=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acovf_x)),height=acovf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.title("Auto Covariance - Random Walk")

plt.subplot(2,3,3)
acorf_x = ts.acf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlags=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acorf_x)),height=acorf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Auto Correlation - Random Walk")


plt.subplot(2,3,4)
dx = [(x[i]-x[i-1]) for i in range(1,len(x))]
plt.plot(dx)
plt.title("Difference of Consecutive Terms")

plt.subplot(2,3,5)
acovf_dx = ts.acovf(dx,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlag=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acovf_dx)),height=acovf_dx,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Auto Covariance - Difference")

plt.subplot(2,3,6)
acorf_dx = ts.acf(dx,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlags=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acorf_dx)),height=acorf_dx,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Auto Correlation - Difference")

Moving Average Process (is a weakly stationary process)

Moving average process of order q, MA(q)
$X_t =Z_t + \beta_1Z_{t-1} + \beta_2Z_{t-2} + \beta_3Z_{t-3} + ..... + \beta_qZ_{t-q}$
are i.i.d. & ~ (, $_2$)
ACF for MA(q) process cuts off a lag q
Why ?

Simulating a MA (2) Process

Below we simulate a MA(2) process
$X_t =Z_t + \beta_1Z_{t-1} + \beta_2Z_{t-2}$
Keeping
$\beta_1 = 0.5$
$\beta_2 = 0.5$
And we observe how auto-correlation coefficient become negligible after lag of 2

In[3]:
import pandas as pd 
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import Toggle
import statsmodels.tsa.stattools as ts

np.random.seed(5)
Z = np.random.normal(size=102)
a = 0.5
b = 0.5
x = [(Z[i]+a*Z[i-1]+b*Z[i-2]) for i in range(2,len(Z))]

plt.figure(figsize=(24,6))
plt.subplot(1,3,1)
plt.title("MA(2) Process")
plt.plot(x)

plt.subplot(1,3,2)
acovf_x = ts.acovf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlag=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acovf_x)),height=acovf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.title("Auto Covariance-MA(2) Process")

plt.subplot(1,3,3)
acorf_x = ts.acf(x,fft=False,adjusted=False,nlags=20)
plt.bar(x=np.arange(len(acorf_x)),height=acorf_x,width=0.3)
plt.axhline(y=0,color='black')
plt.axhline(y=0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=-0.2,color='red',linestyle='--')
plt.title("Auto Correlation-MA(2) Process")
#plt.plot(x)
plt.show()
Toggle.hide_toggle()
